# Adventure POS — Repository rules

Derived from `docs/agent-rules.md`.

## Agent behavior

**Always:** at the **start of a work stream** (feature, non-trivial fix, integration, migration slice, or cross-cutting change), **read `docs/agent-rules.md`** and skim **relevant** docs under `docs/architecture/`, `docs/data-model/`, and `docs/integrations/` or `docs/migrations/` as applicable—including pages marked **future** or **draft**—so implementation matches agreed direction; explain major changes before applying; small incremental edits; focused commits; update docs when setup or architecture changes. For **feature or behavior changes**, review and update **technical documentation** (MkDocs under `docs/`, setup, architecture notes, module READMEs as appropriate) in the same change train when it affects how the system works or how to operate it; **confirm with the human developers** that doc updates match intent before treating documentation as complete.

**Never:** large refactors without approval; delete modules or directories; silent breaking schema changes; commit secrets or credentials.

## Git workflow

- Work on feature branches only; do not commit directly to `main`.
- Use descriptive messages, e.g. `feat(pos): add line item note support`.

## Documentation

- Before coding, use the **documentation-first workflow** in [`docs/agent-rules.md`](docs/agent-rules.md#documentation-first-workflow-mandatory) (architecture, data model, integrations/migrations, future design pages).
- **Published developer docs:** [Event Ops Developer Docs](https://bsileo.github.io/adventure-pos-odoo/) (built from the repo’s MkDocs sources). When surfacing **existing** reference material for developers—not one-off explanations written only in chat—**link to the relevant page on that site** when a matching topic exists there.
- Update `docs/setup.md` if setup changes.
- Update `README.md` if architecture changes.
- Update MkDocs pages under `docs/` when user-facing or developer-facing technical behavior, workflows, or architecture change; keep the published site mentally in sync with source.
- Add module README if module logic becomes complex.

## OpenAI / OpenClaw

- Never store API keys in code; use environment variables only.
- Assume local-only execution unless specified.

## Secrets

- Do NOT store secrets in the repo (use `.env`, not committed).
